## 2. The information we collect

For financial-services clients, we collect more than a typical SaaS
project. Categories include:

- **Identification information** — name, date of birth, government-
  issued identification details, address, occupation. Required by
  PCMLTFA for client identification.
- **Beneficial-ownership information** — for entity clients,
  information about the natural persons who ultimately own or
  control the entity (commonly 25% threshold; verify your sector's
  requirement).
- **PEP / HIO screening data** — politically exposed person and
  head-of-international-organization status; family members and
  close associates where applicable.
- **Financial information** — assets, income, investment knowledge
  and experience, financial goals, risk tolerance, source of
  funds, employment information.
- **Transaction information** — account activity, payments,
  transfers, trades.
- **Account information** — login credentials, account preferences,
  communication preferences.
- **Communications** — emails, secure messages, advisor notes.
- **Technical information** — see baseline policy.

## 3. Why we collect each category

PIPEDA Principle 2 requires that we identify purposes at or before
collection. Our purposes:

- **Identification + KYC** — to comply with FINTRAC client-
  identification obligations and our internal risk-assessment
  controls.
- **Account opening and servicing** — to set up your account, manage
  your relationship with us, and provide the services you've
  retained us for.
- **Suitability and advice** — to provide investment recommendations
  appropriate to your circumstances (where {{PROJECT_NAME}} provides
  advice).
- **Sanctions screening** — to screen against the consolidated
  Canadian sanctions list and other applicable lists.
- **Transaction monitoring** — to detect and report suspicious
  activity per PCMLTFA + internal controls.
- **Communication** — about your account, service updates, and
  regulator-mandated disclosures.
- **Compliance with law** — including responses to lawful authority
  requests, subpoenas, and regulator inquiries.
- **Optional uses** — marketing communications (separate CASL opt-in
  required); analytics and product improvement (subject to consent
  scope).

## 4. Legal basis

Most processing relies on consent (PIPEDA Principle 3). Some
processing relies on statutory permissions or requirements (PIPEDA
s. 7) — notably:

- PCMLTFA client-identification, record-keeping, and reporting
  requirements.
- Securities-regulator filings and disclosures.
- Sanctions-compliance obligations.

You may withdraw consent for non-mandatory processing. Withdrawing
consent for mandatory processing may make us unable to continue our
relationship with you.

## 5. How we share information

We share information with:

- **Subprocessors** — see [`subprocessors.md`](subprocessors.md).
- **Custodian / clearing partner** — if your assets are held by a
  third-party custodian or trades clear through a CIRO-regulated
  dealer.
- **Insurance / surety / professional liability insurers** —
  limited circumstances, typically incident response.
- **Government authorities** — FINTRAC for reportable transactions
  and STRs; OSFI for sanctions-related reports; tax authorities
  under the Income Tax Act and FATCA / CRS where applicable;
  regulators conducting examinations.
- **Lawful authority** — including law enforcement under proper
  legal process.

We do not sell personal information.

## 6. International transfers

Some subprocessors process information outside Canada (see
[`subprocessors.md`](subprocessors.md)). Where information leaves
Canada, contractual safeguards remain in place; however, that
information is subject to the laws of the destination country,
including potential government access requests.

## 7. Retention

Statutory minimums (and our practice) for financial-services records:

- **PCMLTFA records** — at least 5 years from creation; some categories
  longer. Records retrievable to FINTRAC within 30 days of request.
- **Securities records** — per the applicable provincial regulator;
  commonly 7 years.
- **Tax records** — per CRA rules (commonly 6 years from end of last
  tax year the records relate to).
- **Account records after termination** — `[fill in: retention
  windows]`.

When records are no longer needed for any of the above, they are
deleted or de-identified.

## 8. Your rights

Under PIPEDA you have the right to:

- Access your personal information (30-day default response).
- Request correction.
- Withdraw consent (subject to statutory exceptions).
- Make a complaint — first to us at `[fill in: privacy contact]`,
  then to the OPC.

## 9. Safeguards

- TLS in transit; encryption at rest.
- Role-based access, segregation of duties.
- Sanctions screening pipeline.
- Audit logging — see
  [`audit-log-requirements.md`](audit-log-requirements.md).
- Vendor due diligence (see [`subprocessors.md`](subprocessors.md)).
- Breach response runbook — see
  [`breach-response.md`](breach-response.md).

